<b><font size=+1>
List:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2">namedroppers</a>
Subject:    <a href="?t=95837887600026&r=1&w=2">inverse queries / PTR queries</a>
From:       <a href="?a=95837662100002&r=1&w=2">Dennis Rockwell &lt;drockwel () CSNET-SH ! ARPA&gt;</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198509">1985-09-16 17:16:31</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426540&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426540&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

We were wondering how we are *supposed* to find a hostname given an address.
We notice that inverse queries seem to work OK, and that PTR queries to
&lt;reverse IP addr&gt;.in-addr.arpa seem to work OK, but we don't know which
(if any) are going to be supported in the long run.

We will gladly support the PTR-query database for our local nets if
that would be what is desired of us (eg, 8.bbn.com) so that people can
find our names.  Additionally, are we going to be, in effect, the
authority for the domain named 8.in-addr.arpa, or is there going to be
some other naming scheme, such as a CNAME for 8.in-addr.arpa pointing to
8.bbn.com?

Discussion?  Comments?  Are we off in some strange territory (it certainly
doesn't look like Kansas)?

Dennis Rockwell
CSNET Technical Staff

